<h1 id="The-reproduction-number-R">The reproduction number R<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-reproduction-number-R">¶</a></h1><p>In this notebook:</p>

<li>we describe some basics regarding the R value</li>
<li>Study how we can compute R from measured data of cases (or deaths) using two different methods</li>
<li>Apply these methods on different types of fake data with known values of R to recostruct these values.</li>
<li>Show how R is computed on the OSCOVIDA site</li>
</ol>

<h1 id="1.-Reproduction-number-R">1. Reproduction number R<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.-Reproduction-number-R">¶</a></h1><h2 id="1.1-Introduction">1.1 Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.1-Introduction">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_reproduction_number">reproduction number (Wikipedia)</a> can be thought of as the expected number of cases directly generated by one case in a population.</p>
<p>In other words, if a person is infected, he will infect $R$ other people during the duration of his illness. If $n$ people are infected, they will affect $Rn$ people. These $Rn$ people will infect $RRn=R^2n$ people, etc. This leads to the exponential growth of the type $nR^s$ with $s$ being the number of periods over which one generation of infected people will infect the next.</p>
<p>One way to represent $R$ is $R = \beta \,\tau $ where $\beta$ represents an average infection-producing contacts per unit time and $\tau$ the infectious period. The infections period for COVID19 is often assumed to be 4 or 5 days.</p>
<p>For exponential growth with case numbers $n(t)$ increasing as</p>
\begin{equation}
n(t) = n(t_0) R^{t/\tau}, \tag{1}
\end{equation}<p></p>
<p>the logarithmic growth rate $K$ can be used to describe the growth:</p>
\begin{equation}
K = \frac{\mathrm{d} \ln(n)}{\mathrm{d}t}. \tag{2}
\end{equation}<p>The relationship between $R$ and $K$ is</p>
\begin{equation}
R = \exp(K\tau) \tag{3} 
\end{equation}<p>or equivalently $K = \ln(R)/\tau$.</p>
<p>[1] <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_reproduction_number">Basic reproduction number (Wikipedia)</a></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="1.2-Create-data-with-perfect-exponential-growth">1.2 Create data with perfect exponential growth<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.2-Create-data-with-perfect-exponential-growth">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Setup svg rendering in notebook</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">config</span> InlineBackend.figure_formats = ['svg']
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [4]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">n_points</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">15</span>         <span class="c1"># 15 points (=days) in this data set</span>
<span class="n">t</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_points</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>   
<span class="n">tdiff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">0.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_points</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># we need this later</span>
<span class="n">N0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>                <span class="c1"># infections on day 0</span>
<span class="n">tau</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">4</span>               <span class="c1"># average infectious time: 4 days</span>
<span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">2.1</span>               <span class="c1"># R - number of new infections per </span>
<span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">))</span>   <span class="c1"># compute vector n with perfect exponential growth</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'o'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s1">'n(t) = </span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">N0</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s1"> * (</span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s1"> ^ (t/</span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">tau</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s1">))'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"time t [days]"</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"n(t)"</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<h2 id="1.3-Compute-K-and-R-from-this-synthetic-data">1.3 Compute K and R from this synthetic data<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.3-Compute-K-and-R-from-this-synthetic-data">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [6]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">ln_n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">)</span>    
<span class="n">K</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ln_n</span><span class="p">)</span>                 <span class="c1"># equation (2)</span>
<span class="n">R_reconstructed</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">exp</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">K</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>   <span class="c1"># equation (3)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ln_n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'o-'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'ln(n)'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">tdiff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">K</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'x-'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'K = d ln(n) / dt'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">tdiff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">R_reconstructed</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'^-'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'R reconstructed'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'t [days]'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We expect that the reconstructed value <code>R_reconstructed</code> is the same as R when we computed the synthetic data for n(t):</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">R_reconstructed</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

    <div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[8]:</div>




<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>array([2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1, 2.1,
       2.1])</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">R</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

    <div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[9]:</div>




<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>2.1</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We turn this into an automatic test:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">R_reconstructed</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">R</span>    <span class="c1"># checks only first data point</span>
                                  <span class="c1"># where we have perfect agreement</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">R_reconstructed</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">R</span>               <span class="c1"># are all values of R_reconstructed</span>
                                  <span class="c1"># exactly identical to R?</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

    <div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[11]:</div>




<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>array([ 0.00000000e+00,  0.00000000e+00,  0.00000000e+00, -4.44089210e-16,
        4.44089210e-16,  4.44089210e-16,  4.44089210e-16, -1.33226763e-15,
        4.44089210e-16,  4.44089210e-16,  4.44089210e-16,  4.44089210e-16,
       -3.10862447e-15,  4.44089210e-16])</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The values are essentialy the same: deviations are of the order of $10^{-15}$.</p>
<p>We compare all values but allow for some small deviation due to limited machine precision:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [12]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">allclose</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R_reconstructed</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="1.4-Summary">1.4 Summary<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.4-Summary">¶</a></h2><ul>
<li>We know the role of reproduction number $R$ in the exponential growth equation (1) </li>
<li>If we compute daily data points with exponential growth and grow rate $R$, we can use (2) to reconstruct $R$ from the data.</li>
<li>This was just a little exercise to gain confidence with that equation.</li>
</ul>
<p>The potentially harder question is: how do we compute $R$ from <em>measured</em> data which does not show perfect exponential growth.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="2.-Compute-R-from-measured-data">2. Compute R from measured data<a class="anchor-link" href="#2.-Compute-R-from-measured-data">¶</a></h1><h2 id="2.1-Method-1:-as-used-by-Robert-Koch-Institute-(RKI)">2.1 Method 1: as used by Robert Koch Institute (RKI)<a class="anchor-link" href="#2.1-Method-1:-as-used-by-Robert-Koch-Institute-(RKI)">¶</a></h2><p>The bulletin from the Robert Koch institute [2] reports that an average infectious period of $\tau = 4$ days is assumed. Based on that information, the description of the method to compute $R$ (or $R_0$) is [3]</p>
<ul>
<li>compute an average $<n>_1$ of daily new infections over 4 days (say days 0 to 3)</li>
<li>compute an average $<n>_2$ of daily new infections over 4 subsequent days (say days 4 to 7)</li>
<li>compute the quotient $<n>_2 / <n>_1$ </li>
</ul>
<p>The method is references as being reported in [4].</p>
<p>[2] <a href="https://www.rki.de/DE/Content/Infekt/EpidBull/Archiv/2020/Ausgaben/17_20.html">Robert Koch Institute: Epidemiologisches Bulletin 17 | 2020 23. April 2020, page 13 onwards</a></p>
<p>[3] "<em>Bei einer konstanten Generationszeit von 4 Tagen, ergibt sich R als Quotient der Anzahl von Neuerkrankungen in zwei aufeinander folgenden Zeitabschnitten von jeweils 4 Tagen. Der so ermittelte R-Wert wird dem letzten dieser 8 Tage zugeordnet, weil erst dann die gesamte Information vorhanden ist.</em>"</p>
<p>[4] Wallinga J, Lipsitch M: How generation intervals shape the relationship between growth rates and reproductive numbers. <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1766383/">Proceedings of the Royal Society B:
Biological Sciences 2007;274(1609):599–60</a></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="2.2-Method-2:-K-from-d-log(n)/dt-and-tau">2.2 Method 2: K from d log(n)/dt and tau<a class="anchor-link" href="#2.2-Method-2:-K-from-d-log(n)/dt-and-tau">¶</a></h2><p>We can also try to use equations (2) and (3) on measured data to extract $R$, as shown in section 1.3 above.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="3.-Testing-Method-1-and-Method-2">3. Testing Method 1 and Method 2<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.-Testing-Method-1-and-Method-2">¶</a></h1><h2 id="3.1-Approach">3.1 Approach<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.1-Approach">¶</a></h2><p>To test method 1 and method 2, we will create different types of 'synthetic data' that does not show perfect exponential growth. Yet, we create it with a known (but potentially varying) $R$ values, and see how accurately the different methods can reconstruct these $R$ values from the data.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We test this here with the following types of data:</p>
<ul>
<li>Test A: perfect exponential growth (one $R$ value)</li>
<li>Test B: exponential growth with (step) changes in $R$ over time</li>
<li>Test C: adding noise to the data points</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="3.2-Test-A:-perfect-exponential-growth">3.2 Test A: perfect exponential growth<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.2-Test-A:-perfect-exponential-growth">¶</a></h2><h2 id="3.2.1-Test-A---method-1-(RKI)">3.2.1 Test A - method 1 (RKI)<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.2.1-Test-A---method-1-(RKI)">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [13]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">s</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">)</span>    <span class="c1"># turn numpy array into pandas Series</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [15]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">c</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">s</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span>        <span class="c1"># compute the change from day to day </span>
                             <span class="c1"># (i.e. dn/dt, time unit is one day</span>
                             <span class="c1"># and drop the first value for which can't compute dn/dt</span>
                             <span class="c1"># and for which the `diff` method has insert NaN</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [16]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mean1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">c</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>        <span class="c1"># take mean over first 4 days</span>
<span class="n">mean2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">c</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>        <span class="c1"># take mean over next 4 days</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [17]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">quotient</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mean2</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">mean1</span>     <span class="c1"># Compute R as quotient of the two means</span>
<span class="n">quotient</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

    <div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[17]:</div>




<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>2.1</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [18]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">quotient</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">R</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Seems to be okay (for perfect exponential growth)</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="3.2.2-Test-A---method-2:-R-from-d-log(n)/dt-and-tau">3.2.2 Test A - method 2: R from d log(n)/dt and tau<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.2.2-Test-A---method-2:-R-from-d-log(n)/dt-and-tau">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can also try to use equations (2) and (3) on measured data to extract $R$. We have done this above already, but complete it here for completeness:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [19]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">K</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">s</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">R_reconstructed2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">exp</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">K</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">R_reconstructed2</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area">

    <div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[19]:</div>




<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>1     2.1
2     2.1
3     2.1
4     2.1
5     2.1
6     2.1
7     2.1
8     2.1
9     2.1
10    2.1
11    2.1
12    2.1
13    2.1
14    2.1
dtype: float64</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [20]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">allclose</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R_reconstructed2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This also works fine.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="3.3-Test-B:-with-time-dependent-$R$-(step-changes-in-$R$)">3.3 Test B: with time-dependent $R$ (step changes in $R$)<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.3-Test-B:-with-time-dependent-$R$-(step-changes-in-$R$)">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Create-fake-data">Create fake data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Create-fake-data">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>First, we define a function <code>fake_growth</code> that can create test data which exhibits exponential growth of $n(t)$ for where the growth rate (that depends on $R$) can vary as a function of $t$:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">fake_growth</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">delta_t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">float</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="nb">int</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">debug</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="nb">bool</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">"""Expect </span>
<span class="sd">    - delta_t: a vector with ints: each int indicates for how many days</span>
<span class="sd">         R should be constant</span>
<span class="sd">    - Rs: a vector with the corresponding values for R</span>
<span class="sd">    - tau: a constant for the assumption of the average infectious period</span>
<span class="sd">    - N0=1: number of initial cases (for t[0]=0)</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    Assumes exponential growth according to</span>
<span class="sd">    N[i] = N0*(R**(t/tau)) from day i to day i+1 with rate R, where</span>
<span class="sd">    R is specified through delta_t and Rs.</span>
<span class="sd">        </span>
<span class="sd">    Compute and return a time series n. </span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    Also return a vector of days t and a vector of values `Rvec` </span>
<span class="sd">    that show which R values were used for which interval.</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    Returns triplet (n, t, Rvec).</span>
<span class="sd">    </span>
<span class="sd">    """</span>
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">f</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R_</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t_</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">c</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="sd">"""Exponential growth """</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">c</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">R_</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t_</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># check assumptions</span>
    <span class="k">assert</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">delta_t</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Rs</span><span class="p">)</span>

    <span class="c1"># total number of days</span>
    <span class="n">total_days</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">delta_t</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">1</span> 
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">debug</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s2">"Looking at </span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">total_days</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s2"> days."</span><span class="p">)</span>
    
    <span class="c1"># create arrays</span>
    <span class="n">t</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">arange</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">total_days</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">Rvec</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="c1">#dN = np.zeros(shape=t.shape)</span>
    <span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">zeros</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">)</span>   <span class="c1"># final result of function</span>

    <span class="c1">#dN[0] = N0</span>
    <span class="n">counter</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    <span class="n">n</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">N0</span>

 
    <span class="n">counter</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">dt</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">this_R</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">delta_t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rs</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">debug</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="nb">print</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dt</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">this_R</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dt</span><span class="p">):</span>
            <span class="n">n</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">f</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">this_R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">i</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="p">)</span>
            <span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">counter</span> 
            <span class="n">Rvec</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">this_R</span>
            <span class="n">counter</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="mi">1</span>
        <span class="c1"># take the last value as the starting point for next</span>
        <span class="c1"># sequence</span>
        <span class="n">N0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">n</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span>

    <span class="c1"># last point in Rvec is meaningless</span>
    <span class="n">Rvec</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">counter</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">nan</span>
        
    <span class="c1"># n has values for n(t), length total_days</span>
    <span class="c1"># t has values for n(t), length total_days</span>
    <span class="c1"># Rvec[0] has value for R that was valid from t[0] to t[1] and resulted in</span>
    <span class="c1"># value for n[1].</span>
    <span class="c1"># Rvec[1] has value for R that was valid from t[1] to t[1] and resulted in</span>
    <span class="c1"># value for n[2].</span>
    <span class="c1"># Rvec[-1] has np.nan </span>
        
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span>
    

<span class="c1"># Try a simple test set, where tau=1 and R is 2, 3, and 4, for 3 days, 2 days and 1 day, respectively</span>
<span class="c1"># Initial value is N0=1</span>
<span class="n">n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fake_growth</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>A function to test our implementation of the <code>fake_growth</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [25]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">test_fake_growth</span><span class="p">():</span>
    <span class="sd">""" Assume constant growth rate, and expect exponential growth."""</span>
    <span class="n">R_number</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">2.1</span>
    <span class="n">tau</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">4.5</span>
    <span class="n">N0</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">1.3</span>
    <span class="n">n1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fake_growth</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">R_number</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">n2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">N0</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">R_number</span> <span class="o">**</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>   <span class="c1"># correct result</span>
    <span class="n">diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">n2</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">n1</span>                    <span class="c1"># should be zero</span>
    <span class="n">max_err</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s2">"Max error is </span><span class="si">{</span><span class="n">max_err</span><span class="si">}</span><span class="s2">"</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">assert</span> <span class="n">max_err</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="mf">1e-14</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">n1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n2</span>

<span class="n">n1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">test_fake_growth</span><span class="p">();</span>
</pre></div>

</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let's create a plot of the fake data, so we better understand its characteristics:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [26]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># change growth rate</span>
<span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fake_growth</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">2.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># smooth it</span>
<span class="c1"># n_fake = pd.Series(n_fake).rolling(7, center=True, </span>
<span class="c1">#                        win_type='gaussian', </span>
<span class="c1">#                        min_periods=7).mean(std=3)</span>


<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax3</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'-o'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'C1'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">"time dependent R (input)"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="s1">'.-'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'C3'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s1">'d log(n)/dt)'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">n_fake</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># turn into pandas.Series to get diff() method</span>
<span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bar</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'daily new cases'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'time [days]'</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="n">ax1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(),</span><span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">();</span>
</pre></div>

<h3 id="Now-we-create-some-fake-data-that-will-be-used-to-test-the-different-methods-of-computing-R-from-it.">Now we create some fake data that will be used to test the different methods of computing R from it.<a class="anchor-link" href="#Now-we-create-some-fake-data-that-will-be-used-to-test-the-different-methods-of-computing-R-from-it.">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [29]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fake_growth</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">25</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mf">2.5</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">N0</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax3</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Rvec</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'-o'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'C1'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">"time dependent R"</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">)),</span> <span class="s1">'.-'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'C3'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s1">'d log(n)/dt)'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">n_fake</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Series</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="p">)</span>  <span class="c1"># turn into pandas.Series to get diff() method</span>
<span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">bar</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">n_fake</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'daily new cases'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'time [days]'</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="n">ax1</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(),</span><span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">ax3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">();</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="3.3.1-Test-Method-1:-RKI-for-time-dependent-$R$">3.3.1 Test Method 1: RKI for time dependent $R$<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.3.1-Test-Method-1:-RKI-for-time-dependent-$R$">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [33]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Smoothing makes things a lot better:</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'smooth_c'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'c_td'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">center</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> 
                                    <span class="n">win_type</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'gaussian'</span><span class="p">,</span> 
                                    <span class="n">min_periods</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># but important to have min_periods the same as the rolling period</span>

<span class="c1"># compute the mean over 4 days</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'c_td'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># compute the time dependent R that  is reconstructed:</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'R_td-recon'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shift</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="c1"># show R_td (known) next to R_td-recon (reconstructed)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'R_td'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'R_td-recon'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'n_td'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="3.3.3-Summary-time-dependent-$R$">3.3.3 Summary time dependent $R$<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.3.3-Summary-time-dependent-$R$">¶</a></h2><p>Both methods recover the right value of $R$ after a period of approximately $\tau$ (which is 4 days here). Method 1 overshoots and undershoots following sudden changes of $R$.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="3.4-Test-2:-data-with-random-noise">3.4 Test 2: data with random noise<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.4-Test-2:-data-with-random-noise">¶</a></h2><p>In reality, not only does the R value change through change in behaviour, we also have an incomplete and noisy measurement. Here we try to add some noise and reconstruct $R$ from the data despite the noise.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [41]:</div>

<p>The noise seems amplified in the reconstructed R.</p>
<h4 id="Let's-try-some-smoothing-of-the-noisy-data:">Let's try some smoothing of the noisy data:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Let's-try-some-smoothing-of-the-noisy-data:">¶</a></h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [48]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'smooth_c'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'c_td'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">center</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> 
                                    <span class="n">win_type</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'gaussian'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">min_periods</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'smooth_c'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>


<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'R_td-recon'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shift</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'R_td'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'R_td-recon'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'n_td'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'mean4d'</span><span class="p">]]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>While the reconstructed $R$ values are not exactly 2.0, they now range between ~1.4 and 2.5; so less than about 25% relative error (that's after smoothing the data).</p>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'smooth_n'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'n_td'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">center</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span>

<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'K'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'smooth_n'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">periods</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shift</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'R_td-recon2'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">exp</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'K'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">t</span><span class="p">[:</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'R_td-recon2'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="s1">'^'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'C2'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="sa">f</span><span class="s1">'R_td-recon2'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="3.4.3-Summary">3.4.3 Summary<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.4.3-Summary">¶</a></h2><p>Method 1 and 2 perform similarly for data with random noise. Smoothing of the input data is important.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Conclusions">Conclusions<a class="anchor-link" href="#Conclusions">¶</a></h2><ul>
<li><p>Reconstruction of R from perfect exponential growth works using both methods.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Reconstruction of R from exponential growth with sudden rate changes works well for method 2. 
For method 1, the algorithm seems stable, and returns the correct value R (after ~tau days) if R is constant
but based on the test data used here is less accurate than method 2.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Use smoothing for the case numbers (or the diff of the case numbers) seems to improve estimates, and is important 
(in particular to deal with noise in the data).</p>
</li>
<li><p>It is important for the rolling averages (both for the smoothing of the diff, and for the
4-day average) to use all data points, and not to ignore some. If we use 'min_values=' to allow fewer 
data points, the reconstructed R values show systematic errors at the beginning and end of the interval. 
(This is not show above but has been explored separately.)</p>
</li>
<li><p>For now, we use Method 1 in the computation of R on the <a href="https://oscovida.github.io">OSCOVIDA site</a>. 
The relevant source code is in 
<a href="https://github.com/oscovida/oscovida/blob/master/oscovida/oscovida.py#L866">the file oscovida.py</a> in the function <code>plot_reproduction_number</code>, which in turn calls <code>compute_R</code>.</p>
<ul>
<li>This is for historical reasons and a lack of time for more systematic testing of method 2.</li>
<li>using method 2, we may also get rid of the lag of $\tau$ days in the computation of R</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="4.-Demo:-compute-R-with-OSCOVIDA">4. Demo: compute R with OSCOVIDA<a class="anchor-link" href="#4.-Demo:-compute-R-with-OSCOVIDA">¶</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [53]:</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">cases</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">deaths</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">oscovida</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">get_country_data</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Germany"</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="c1"># change, smooth, smooth2 = oscovida.compute_daily_change(cases)</span>
<span class="n">oscovida</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_reproduction_number</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cases</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">"C1"</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Compare with more manual calculation</span>

<span class="c1"># compute change from day to day</span>
<span class="n">diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cases</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="c1"># smooth that change</span>
<span class="n">smooth_diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">center</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">win_type</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'gaussian'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Compute R using method 1</span>
<span class="n">R</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">oscovida</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">compute_R</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">smooth_diff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tau</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># plot as thin line</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">R</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">R</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s2">"g"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="sa">r</span><span class="s2">"R (estimated with $\tau$=4 days using RKI algorithm)"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylim</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="mf">0.7</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">]);</span>
</pre></div>

entry.title: Tutorial: Installing OSCOVIDA
entry.summary:
OSCOVIDA Tutorial: installation¶

Use OSCOVIDA in the cloud¶

To use OSCOVIDA in the cloud, you can go to this link, and can see all available Notebooks (most of which analyses one region, but you can also find the tutorial notebooks that start with the name tutorial). Or you can create your own notebook at that point.

  border-radius: 2px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: border-box;
  -webkit-box-sizing: border-box;
  border-width: 1px;
  border-style: solid;
  border-color: transparent;
  width: 100%;
  padding: 5px;

  margin: 0px;
  outline: none;
  position: relative;
  overflow: visible;
}

}

/* The following gets added to the <head> if it is detected that the user has a
 * monospace font with inconsistent normal/bold/italic height.  See
 * notebookmain.js.  Such fonts will have keywords vertically offset with
 * respect to the rest of the text.  The user should select a better font.
 * See: https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/1503
 *
 * .CodeMirror span {
 *      vertical-align: bottom;
 * }
 */
.CodeMirror {
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Changed from 1em to our global default */
  font-size: 14px;
  height: auto;
  /* Changed to auto to autogrow */
  background: none;
  /* Changed from white to allow our bg to show through */
}
.CodeMirror-scroll {
  /*  The CodeMirror docs are a bit fuzzy on if overflow-y should be hidden or visible.*/
  /*  We have found that if it is visible, vertical scrollbars appear with font size changes.*/
  overflow-y: hidden;
  overflow-x: auto;
}
.CodeMirror-lines {
  /* In CM2, this used to be 0.4em, but in CM3 it went to 4px. We need the em value because */
  /* we have set a different line-height and want this to scale with that. */
  /* Note that this should set vertical padding only, since CodeMirror assumes
       that horizontal padding will be set on CodeMirror pre */
  padding: 0.4em 0;
}
.CodeMirror-linenumber {
  padding: 0 8px 0 4px;
}
.CodeMirror-gutters {
  border-bottom-left-radius: 2px;
  border-top-left-radius: 2px;
}
.CodeMirror pre {
  /* In CM3 this went to 4px from 0 in CM2. This sets horizontal padding only,
    use .CodeMirror-lines for vertical */
  padding: 0 0.4em;
  border: 0;
  border-radius: 0;
}

  border-left: 1.4px solid black;

<h1 id="OSCOVIDA-Tutorial:-installation">OSCOVIDA Tutorial: installation<a class="anchor-link" href="#OSCOVIDA-Tutorial:-installation">¶</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Use-OSCOVIDA-in-the-cloud">Use OSCOVIDA in the cloud<a class="anchor-link" href="#Use-OSCOVIDA-in-the-cloud">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To use OSCOVIDA in the cloud, you can go to <a href="https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/oscovida/binder/master?filepath=ipynb">this link</a>, 
and can see all available Notebooks (most of which analyses one region, but you can also find the tutorial notebooks that start with the name <code>tutorial</code>). Or you can create your own notebook at that point.</p>
<p>What technically happens is that (through the <a href="http://mybinder.org">binder project</a>) a container (a bit like a small virtual machine) is created just for you at that point on a server somewhere on the planet. You can use this container from your browser, but any commands you execute are actually executed on this server somewhere else (i.e. "in the cloud"). You can use this container as long as you like, but there is a time-out: after 10 minutes of inactivity, your session will be closed.</p>
<p>This way of using OSCOVIDA in the cloud is very convenient, because you don't need to install any software on your own computer/tablet etc.</p>
<p>However, there are a number of limitations to be aware:</p>
<ul>
<li>any interactive session you have, will be deleted after 10 minutes of inactivity</li>
<li>at that point, your notebooks is also lost</li>
<li>if you want to keep the notebook, you can go to <code>File -> Download as -> Notebook (.ipynb)</code> before your session expires</li>
<li>if you have have saved such a notebook, you can upload it and then continue to work on it in your next session.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Use-OSCOVIDA-on-your-own-computer">Use OSCOVIDA on your own computer<a class="anchor-link" href="#Use-OSCOVIDA-on-your-own-computer">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Alternatively, you can install OSCOVIDA on your own computer, and then all the files you create and modify are saved locally on your computer.</p>
<p>OSCOVIDA is a python package, and makes use of other Python libraries such as <code>matplotlib</code> for creation of plots and <code>numpy</code> and <code>pandas</code> for data handling.</p>
<p>If you know Python and have Python (version 3.6 or newer) installed already, then you can install <code>oscovida</code> using <code>pip install oscovida</code>.</p>
<p>If you have no Python installation, or are new to Python, then we recommend to download and install the <a href="https://www.anaconda.com/products/individual">Anaconda Python distribution</a>. Some more detailed instructions are available <a href="https://fangohr.github.io/blog/installation-of-python-spyder-numpy-sympy-scipy-pytest-matplotlib-via-anaconda.html">here</a>. Once this is installed, you need to install the <code>oscovida</code> package within this Python environment. To do this, type <code>pip install oscovida</code> at a prompt.</p>
<p>Then start a Jupyter Notebook. Within than type</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">oscovida</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The next line is not required: it instructs Jupyter notebook to use
vector plots instead of bitmaps, and thus produces generally nicer graphs:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [2]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="o">%</span><span class="k">config</span> InlineBackend.figure_formats = ['svg']
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>If no error message is printed, your system is working. in that case, try a first command, for example:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">oscovida</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">overview</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Italy"</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The working assumption is that during the weekend fewer numbers are captured or reported. The analysis below seems to confirm this.</p>
<p>We compute a discrete Fourier transform of the data, and expect a peak at a frequency corresponding to a period of 7 days.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Data-selection">Data selection<a class="anchor-link" href="#Data-selection">¶</a></h2><p>We start with data from 1st March as numbers before were small. It is convenient to take a number of days that can be divided by seven (for alignment of the freuency axis in Fourier space, so we choose 63 days from 1st of March):</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">data</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">cases</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'2020-03-01'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="s1">'2020-05-03'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="c1"># compute daily change</span>
<span class="n">diff</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="c1"># plot data points (corresponding to bars in figure above:)</span>
<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">diff</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'-C1'</span><span class="p">,</span> 
        <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'daily new cases Germany'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">fig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">autofmt_xdate</span><span class="p">()</span>  <span class="c1"># avoid x-labels overlap</span>
<span class="c1"># How many data points (=days) have we got?</span>
<span class="n">diff</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span>
</pre></div>

<h2 id="Compute-the-frequency-spectrum">Compute the frequency spectrum<a class="anchor-link" href="#Compute-the-frequency-spectrum">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="c1"># compute power density spectrum </span>
<span class="n">change_F</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fft</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fft</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">diff2</span><span class="p">))</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="mi">2</span>
<span class="c1"># determine appropriate frequencies</span>
<span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">change_F</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span>
<span class="n">freq</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fft</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fftfreq</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">d</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># We skip values at indices 0, 1 and 2: these are large because we have a finite </span>
<span class="c1"># sequence and not substracted the mean from the data set</span>
<span class="c1"># We also only plot the the first n/2 frequencies as for high n, we get negative</span>
<span class="c1"># frequencies with the same data content as the positive ones.</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">freq</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="o">//</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">change_F</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="o">//</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="s1">'o-C3'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'frequency [cycles per day]'</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
